<HEADLINE>
<P>
NHL NEGOTIATORS TALK, BUT THAT'S ALL; HOCKEY: LITTLE PROGRESS MADE IN LABOR 
DISPUTE, DESPITE REPORTS THAT SIDES HAVE SOFTENED THEIR STANCES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HELENE ELLIOTT, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The fate of the NHL season remained uncertain Thursday, after a meeting 
between representatives of the league and the players' association produced no 
indication that they had resolved their major differences. 
</P>
<P>
 Reports that they had moved closer to a deal that would result in the season 
starting Dec. 1 were contradicted by Bob Goodenow, the NHLPA's executive 
director. 
</P>
<P>
 "Unfortunately, no significant progress was made," he said after the 
seven-hour session in Buffalo, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
 The negotiators agreed to speak by phone today and will discuss whether to 
convene this weekend or early next week. Goodenow was to brief players on the 
negotiations Thursday, before the start of a three-game charity exhibition 
tournament in Hamilton, Canada. 
</P>
<P>
 The talks, which appeared to reach a stalemate last week, took an optimistic 
turn Monday after sources among owners and players said meaningful compromises 
had been made. Players reportedly had agreed to accept an entry-level salary 
system and limited salary arbitration in exchange for more liberal free agency. 
Owners were said to be ready to drop their payroll levy proposal, which players 
had rejected as a salary restraint, and were prepared to restore most of the 
economic rollbacks they imposed Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 However, roadblocks remain, including the players' demand to be paid in full 
this season, regardless of the number of games missed. Owners, whose revenue 
has been reduced by the cancellation of six home games each, are balking at 
that. 
</P>
<P>
 Sources said owners also don't consider the players' acceptance of an 
entry-level salary structure enough compensation for dropping the levy and will 
ask for other concessions. Owners also have not restored game rosters to 18 
skaters and two goalies from 17 and two, a cut instituted during training camp. 
</P>
<P>
 As the lockout began its 42nd day, player agent Rich Winter announced plans to 
create a new league if the season is wiped out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
