<HEADLINE>
<P>
PANEL CALLS FOR BROADER WORLD HISTORY LESSONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A federal education panel today will release a new curriculum guide for 
teaching world history to students in grades 5 through 12 that asks teachers to 
redirect their scope beyond old Europe and toward "a genuine globe-encompassing 
history." 
</P>
<P>
 The new guidelines encourage a refocusing on non-traditional hallmarks of 
history such as China's Song dynasty, which developed paper currency and 
gunpowder and printing, panel members said. 
</P>
<P>
 The standards, which are voluntary, will retain the study of the Greek 
city-states and the Roman Empire but add the Mauryan Empire in India and the 
Olmec civilization, which influenced the Zapotec and Mayan civilizations. 
</P>
<P>
 The standards were already under fire from conservatives who say they belittle 
Western civilization in the name of multiculturalism. 
</P>
<P>
 The architect of the guidelines -- the UCLA Center for History in the Schools 
-- said it stands by its plan, which was approved by hundreds of historians and 
educators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
