<HEADLINE>
<P>
REAGAN STILL ACTIVE, WIFE SAYS DURING BOOK SIGNING; PUBLISHING: ADMIRERS FLOCK 
TO REAGAN LIBRARY TO GREET THE FORMER FIRST LADY, WHO AUTOGRAPHED COPIES OF HER 
AUTOBIOGRAPHY, 'MY TURN.' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Former President Ronald Reagan has been doing "just fine," riding horses and 
chopping wood on his Santa Barbara County ranch since telling the American 
public last weekend that he has Alzheimer's disease, his wife said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 "We hope coming out like that will help people," Nancy Reagan said of the 
two-page handwritten letter her husband released last weekend. "His letter said 
it all." 
</P>
<P>
 A crush of well-wishers bearing cards, prayers and warm words for the former 
President greeted Mrs. Reagan on Thursday as she signed copies of her 
autobiography at the Ronald Reagan Presidential Library near Simi Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Giddy in her presence, they edged up to where she sat, whispered their best 
wishes and handed over copies of "My Turn." 
</P>
<P>
 As she etched her name into the books in a neat, careful hand, some visitors 
assured her gently, "Your husband's in our prayers," then sidled away with 
flustered grins. 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Reagan thanked them, quietly, and smiled back. 
</P>
<P>
 For some, it was a momentous experience -- meeting this Republican icon 
face-to-face two days after her party seized control of Congress for the first 
time in four decades. 
</P>
<P>
 But it was also a chance to wish the Reagans well, to deliver cards through 
her to him and -- for at least one visitor -- to offer the former President 
pamphlets on Alzheimer's disease. About 100,000 people die of the mind-damaging 
illness every year. 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Reagan told a reporter she is "very pleased" with the power shift in 
Congress. "But," she said bluntly, "my thoughts are with my husband right now." 
</P>
<P>
 Then she turned back to her task, signing books, waving to schoolchildren, 
thanking her fans and smiling into the staccato blaze of a hundred snapshots. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Clutching a signed, red-bound copy of "My Turn," Rose M. Sternad waited in the 
cash-register line with her son, basking in the afterglow of a few seconds with 
Mrs. Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's something we've dreamed of for a long time, meeting her," said Sternad, 
56, a retired secretary from La Puente. "It's so beautiful, and for me it was 
just the cherry on top of everything that's happened since the election." 
</P>
<P>
 Waiting in line to pay $35 apiece for their books, some relived their brief 
words with the former First Lady. 
</P>
<P>
 "I told her I was praying for her husband, and she said, 'I appreciate your 
prayers,' " recalled Dolores Hale, a 57-year-old Simi Valley homemaker. "It was 
real sweet." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Reagan rebuffed one man, signing his copy of her book but spurning a 
stack of photos and matted prints of her and the former President that he 
offered in a trembling hand. 
</P>
<P>
 "She said 'no,' " groused the man, an autograph collector who would not give 
his name as he left the gift shop. 
</P>
<P>
 For others, she smiled at their crying infants and fidgety children, quietly 
shared a word or two and signed stacks of books -- more than 600 copies in all. 
</P>
<P>
 Darin Plotnick, 32, an insurance worker and self-described Democrat from 
Sherman Oaks, said he came "because of who she is, rather than what she is." 
</P>
<P>
 "She came through all the negative press and the opinions that were going on 
for a while there," Plotnick said. "She came through it and faced it all." 
</P>
<P>
 The Associated Press contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
